Technology and criminal behaviour

Basic technology and crime interaction

  • Technology-enabled offences: traditional crimes facilitated by the use of technology (e.g., identity theft)

  • Technology-dependent offences: crimes that exist because of technology (e.g., ransomware)

Interaction between ICT and crime (Viano, 2017)

  • “Ordinary” criminal offenses committed by means of information and communication technology (ICT).
  • Crimes directed against the proper functioning of ICT systems
  • Crimes against interests that are web-specific

Typology of technology-facilited crimes

  • Techno-crime AS work: crime opportunities provided by ICT and exploited by individuals as their source income.

  • Techno-crime AT work: crime opportunities facilited by ICT during the course of an individual’s legitimate work.

  • Techno-crime AFTER work: crime opportunities facilitated by ICT and exploited by individuals during their leisure time.

Examples

  • Techno-crime AS work: Internet fraud schemes, telemarketing fraud schemes, identity theft, credit card fraud, phishing for profit, internet sex crimes, sale of stolen data, internet piracy, etc.

  • Techno-crime AT work: Embezzelment, money laundering, financial fraud, credit card fraud by employees, corporate espionage, theft/sale private information, spreading viruses or malicious code, etc.

  • Techno-crime AFTER work: internet sex crimes, internet sex crimes, cyber-terrorism, hacking, illegal access to data, etc.

The Deep Web and the darknet

The Deep Web

“… refers to all online material, including the darknet and mainstream sites that is not indexed or accessible through serarch engines”

The surface web, deep web and darknet

The Darknet

  • Designed to guarantee anonymity by the US Naval Research Laboratory
  • Many types of users: criminals, criminal organizations, government workers, academics, terorrist organizations, whistle blowers, journalists, etc.
  • Content not available through normal browsers
  • .Onion websites
  • TOR (The Onion Router)

The Darknet and crime

  • Market place for selling illicit commodities and services
    • Drugs
    • Stolen data
    • Illegal weapons
    • Sex trade
    • Illegal content
    • Murder for hire
    • Hacking
    • Cyber attacks
  • Virtually undectectable
  • Cryptocurrency for transactions
